    &lt;/dependency&gt;

There is a possible conflict between &quot;spring-boot-starter-web&quot; and &quot;spring-boot-starter-tomcat&quot;. The former already takes care of tomcat.

Read more here: 
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/33419823/spring-boot-starter-tomcat-vs-spring-boot-starter-web

Your pom.xml contains both the `spring-boot-starter-web` and `spring-boot-starter-tomcat` dependencies. This is redundant as the former has a default embedded tomcat.

Take out the `spring-boot-starter-tomcat` dependency, that is,
```
&lt;dependency&gt;
            &lt;groupId&gt;org.springframework.boot&lt;/groupId&gt;
            &lt;artifactId&gt;spring-boot-starter-tomcat&lt;/artifactId&gt;
        &lt;/dependency&gt;
```

 Run `mvn clean install` and then run the spring application once you get a BUILD SUCCESS

If you want a WAR type spring boot application, then remove `spring.main.web-application-type=none` from your application.yml file.Also do as below in build.gradle.

    implementation(&quot;org.springframework.boot:spring-boot-starter-web&quot;) {
        exclude module: &quot;spring-boot-starter-tomcat&quot;
    }
    providedRuntime(&#39;org.springframework.boot:spring-boot-starter-tomcat&#39;)

After that clean and refresh your dependency as below:

    gradlew clean build

    gradlew --refresh-dependencies

For me, in Windows, the important things was **install** maven client:

-https://maven.apache.org/install.html , 

-obviously extract folder from zip, 

-add the bin folder in the enviroment path.

After that **RESTART** intellij or Eclipse and run in the root folder of your app:

-**remove** tomcat dependency 

    &lt;dependency&gt;
    &lt;groupId&gt;org.springframework.boot&lt;/groupId&gt;
    &lt;artifactId&gt;spring-boot-starter-tomcat&lt;/artifactId&gt;
    &lt;scope&gt;provided&lt;/scope&gt;
    &lt;/dependency&gt;

-launch command: **mvn clean install** (as told in the previous answers)

-Start the app

Without this command the dependency will not refresh and the error will remains.

This is because of conflict in `spring.boot.starter.tomcat` dependency. It is already there in `spring.boot.starter.web`.  &lt;br&gt;
Exclude the `spring.boot.starter.tomcat` will resolve the issue. 
   

    &lt;dependency&gt;
        &lt;groupId&gt;org.springframework.boot&lt;/groupId&gt;
        &lt;artifactId&gt;spring-boot-starter-web&lt;/artifactId&gt;
        &lt;exclusions&gt;
            &lt;exclusion&gt;
                &lt;groupId&gt;org.springframework.boot&lt;/groupId&gt;
                &lt;artifactId&gt;spring-boot-starter-tomcat&lt;/artifactId&gt;
            &lt;/exclusion&gt;
        &lt;/exclusions&gt;
    &lt;/dependency&gt;

